Garbage collection in one breath.

The java virtual machine tracks which heap objects are reachable from your live code, starting from local variables, static fields, and a handful of other root sets. Any object the garbage collector cannot reach is, by definition, garbage. The collector reclaims its memory. You never call free in Java.

The generational hypothesis is the assumption every modern garbage collector builds on. It says that most objects die young. The vast majority of allocations are short lived. To exploit this, the heap is split into a young generation and an old generation. New objects are born in the young generation. Collections of the young generation are cheap, because most objects are already dead by the time a collection runs. Objects that survive several young generation collections get promoted to the old generation. Collections of the old generation happen less often, and they are more expensive.

You do not tune garbage collection unless something specific forces you to. The defaults are good. When you do need to tune, the three modern collectors worth knowing are G one, Z G C, and Shenandoah. G one is the default since Java nine. It targets mostly short pauses, with a reasonable balance between throughput and latency. It is the right choice for most workloads. Z G C is a sub millisecond pause collector designed for very large heaps and latency sensitive services. Shenandoah is similar to Z G C in design and pause characteristics. It is favoured in the open J D K distribution from Red Hat. You select a collector with a java virtual machine flag. Use G one G C. Use Z G C. Use Shenandoah G C.
